    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **Lawrence Butler** (74.56) stands as our premier offensive option. Despite hitting in the lower third of the order, he benefits from a highly favorable matchup against Wacha, where a 10% park boost and a 15% skill advantage against the starter create an ideal environment for production. **Daulton Varsho** (68.40) and **Cal Raleigh** (66.37) also project as foundational pieces. **Daulton Varsho** benefits significantly from a favorable park factor and a 13% SP skill bump, while **Cal Raleigh** continues to be an undervalued asset in the #2 spot, where his xwOBA profile and order-based boost compensate for the inherent volatility of a catcher.\n\nWe are navigating a few tactical hurdles, specifically with **Geraldo Perdomo** (59.46) hovering just beneath our \"Strong\" tier. While his leadoff spot provides a +10% efficiency floor, his output remains marginal compared to the high-upside plays. The closest decision on our bench was **Gleyber Torres** (37.91); he was strictly excluded because his matchup against the elite Ritchie (2.92 xERA) plummeted his score well below our 40.0 \"Zebras\" floor. Consequently, we have opted to play for matchups rather than reputation, keeping **Gleyber Torres** and **Wenceel Perez** sidelined. We are also monitoring the fallout from **Bryson Stott**, whose game has been scrubbed due to a rainout, ensuring he occupies a zero-point bench slot today. **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (66.29) remains a high-floor start, particularly with his aggressive baserunning potential providing a vital boost in our focus category of Stolen Bases against a pitcher with a notably slow delivery to the plate.",
